  "applications": [
    "If you are early in a career or entering a new environment, your first job is not to be excellent — it is to be noticed. Pick one visible, specific thing that sets you apart: an unusual way of presenting work, a style of thinking out loud in meetings, a particular domain you own completely. Make it something people can describe to someone else in one sentence. Excellence that no one can attach a name to does nothing for you.",
    "When you need to break into a conversation or field where you have no standing, consider attacking the most prominent idea, person, or institution in that space — thoughtfully, wittily, on substance. It transfers visibility. The key is to attack the idea rather than the person, and to do it with enough intelligence that people can't dismiss you as merely provocative. Done well, one sharp piece of dissent can do years of networking's work.",
    "Introduce deliberate unpredictability into your behavior at regular intervals. Not instability — controlled surprise. Do something that doesn't fit the pattern others have assembled for you. Say something unexpected in a meeting where your position is assumed. Take a public stance no one predicted. When people feel they fully understand you, they stop watching closely. Disrupting that certainty makes you interesting again.",
    "Never compete for attention in the presence of someone whose standing you depend on. In any room where your superior is present, your job is to enhance their visibility, not claim your own. The one moment of self-promotion that overshadows them will undo months of goodwill. Study Lola Montez: brilliant at commanding attention everywhere else, catastrophically bad at knowing when not to."
  ],
  "reflection": "Think about the environments where you most want to be seen — your workplace, your industry, your social world. Are you genuinely visible there, or do you assume that doing good work is sufficient? What specific, distinctive thing would make someone who barely knows you describe you to a stranger?"
