    "Time and energy are the real currencies of power — and they are finite. Every hour you spend doing work that someone else could do is an hour you are not thinking, positioning, or building. Greene's argument is not laziness; it is resource allocation. The person who learns to leverage other people's labor operates at a scale the solitary worker can never match.",
    "Credit is as valuable as the work itself — often more so. The public cannot see the labor behind a creation; they see only the name attached to it. Tesla built the alternating-current system. Westinghouse's name went on the patents. Marconi used Tesla's research to invent radio. Tesla died in poverty. The lesson is not that theft is admirable — it is that failing to protect and claim your credit is a form of strategic negligence.",
