    "Nikola Tesla was one of the most brilliant inventors in history — responsible for the AC electrical system that still powers the world, the induction motor, and the foundational research behind radio. He worked eighteen-hour days for Edison, redesigned the dynamo completely in under a year, and was told the $50,000 Edison had promised was an 'American joke.' He sold his AC patents to Westinghouse for a fraction of their worth under financial pressure. Marconi used his research to claim the radio patent. Other scientists stepped forward to claim credit for his AC work. He refused the Edison Medal in his impoverished old age, calling it an insult that would decorate his body while his mind starved for recognition. He died alone in a New York hotel room. His genius was never in question; his failure to secure, protect, and politically defend his credit cost him everything.",

